<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
  <Document><name>Travel Itinerary Map</name>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Tha Rae</name>
      <description><![CDATA[One of my favorite places in Sakon Nakhon, and a spot that’s pretty unique to this province, is , a historic Christian town home to the largest Catholic community in Thailand. The town features many stunning French colonial buildings, some of which have been converted into charming cafes and restaurants, while others remain preserved and untouched, just waiting for you to explore.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/3fo65fnoryWYkpXG9">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Tha Rae, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>abandoned colonial house</name>
      <description><![CDATA[While you are here, be sure to spend some time and explore the criss-crossing streets to Tha Rae. You might stumble upon a hidden gem like this  that the forest has taken over.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/heubZfc1uiuQERPY8">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>abandoned colonial house, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Udomdechwat Mansion</name>
      <description><![CDATA[The centerpiece of Tha Rae is , an old 2-storey colonial building that was once a private residence but has since been converted into a cafe. It has been restored with its vivid yellow colored exterior and fitted with vintage decor and modern amenities. You can escape the heat and take a break here with refreshing drinks before continuing to explore Tha Rae.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/EFHgPemq1gUXeZGLA">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Udomdechwat Mansion, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>breakfast spot</name>
      <description><![CDATA[You’ll also find several more colonial buildings along the main road in Tha Rae, including one that’s been converted into a charming , perfect for an early morning bite. There are also a couple more historic structures right in front of the Cathedral of St. Michael the Archangel. Be sure to take some time to explore Tha Rae on foot! You can explore anytime you like, but it's best to come in the morning when it's not too hot outside.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/MTPKrhvJVizve9Tz6">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>breakfast spot, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Cathedral of St Michael the Archangel</name>
      <description><![CDATA[is one of the oldest and largest Catholic cathedrals in Thailand, and it is one of the main attractions of Tha Rae. In a country full of Buddhist temples, the Cathedral and its futuristic design are not sights you get to see every day.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/2DEBUdULQnSr3mQV8">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Cathedral of St Michael the Archangel, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Kasetsart University Lotus and Waterlily Park</name>
      <description><![CDATA[Located not far from Tha Rae, you’ll find , a charming park featuring a spacious lotus pond with boardwalks and pavilions perfect for relaxing. The park was established by Kasetsart University, one of Thailand’s most well-known universities, whose main campus is in Bangkok. Fun fact, the university is actually not too far from my home in Bangkok 😉.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/or7Uwxm4VvDeiNgT9">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Kasetsart University Lotus and Waterlily Park, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Phu Phan Museum</name>
      <description><![CDATA[For those who are interested in the history of Sakon Nakhon, a great place to check out while you are in Sakon Nakhon City is , a well-curated local museum that celebrates the region's history, culture, and natural heritage located in a large park right next to the Nong Han Lake.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/9mTYBMqnyoKSrose9">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Phu Phan Museum, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Wat Phra That Choeng Chum Worawihan</name>
      <description><![CDATA[is the most sacred and highly revered temple in Sakon Nakhon located right in the city center and it is considered one of the finest examples of Lao-style Buddhist architecture in Isaan.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/PCddu62oV66sW77N9">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Wat Phra That Choeng Chum Worawihan, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Sakon Nakhon Walking Street</name>
      <description><![CDATA[Right next to the temple, you’ll find the , though to be honest, it’s not much of a walking street, with only a handful of local vendors setting up small stands. What makes it worth checking out, however, is what they’re selling: indigo-dyed cotton products, a craft that Sakon Nakhon is well known for.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/AEmDJGEVgGh5zqvp6">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Sakon Nakhon Walking Street, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Wat Tham Pha Daen</name>
      <description><![CDATA[Sakon Nakhon is home to some truly impressive forest temples, and one of my favorites is . Located amid the lush Phu Phan Mountains, about 20–35 km from Sakon Nakhon city, this Buddhist temple is full of colorful sculptures, stunning viewpoints, and much more, waiting for you to explore.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/UGW8Zix6QsjSAvC6A">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Wat Tham Pha Daen, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Phra That Phu Phek</name>
      <description><![CDATA[One of my favorite ancient Khmer ruins in Sakon Nakhon is , located at the top of Phu Phek mountain about 35 km west of Sakon Nakhon City. Believed to have been constructed between the 11th to 12th centuries, this sacred site goes to show just how far and wide the Khmer Empire was back in the day.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/eRcygvVWPkQgTMGU6">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Phra That Phu Phek, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Phrathat Narai Cheng Weng</name>
      <description><![CDATA[For a more accessible Khmer temple, you can also check out , a highly revered Khmer ruin located not too far from Sakon Nakhon Airport. Believed to have been constructed during the 11th century, this sandstone tower stands on a laterite base and is adorned with intricate carvings depicting Hindu deities and mythological scenes.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/oyrwSDJhnCsPsSXw5">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Phrathat Narai Cheng Weng, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Prasat Ku Phanna</name>
      <description><![CDATA[If you are planning to drive from Sakon Nakhon to Udon Thani, you might want to make a quick stop at , a small Khmer structure located in the middle of a rice field not too far from the highway connecting the 2 provinces together.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/Wp5cokaxEg4DHKdJ6">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Prasat Ku Phanna, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Pak Mor Paris</name>
      <description><![CDATA[Looking for a place to eat in Sakon Nakhon? One of the most famous spots is , a local restaurant serving a small but delicious selection of Thai-style Vietnamese dishes like Vietnamese pizza and fresh rice noodle wraps, all at affordable prices.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/8zYiQky7eWAswGXo8">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Pak Mor Paris, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>UDD Bistro & Cafe</name>
      <description><![CDATA[If you're visiting Tha Rae Village, be sure to stop by , a charming spot housed inside Udomdechwat Mansion, an old two-story colonial residence that has been beautifully restored and transformed into a café. With its vivid yellow exterior, vintage decor, and modern amenities, it’s a lovely blend of old and new.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/t6HZgaXHUDaNWNYDA">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>UDD Bistro & Cafe, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Ban Fa Prong Restaurant</name>
      <description><![CDATA[is one of my favorite places to eat in Sakon Nakhon. The restaurant offers a wide variety of dishes, both Thai and Western, along with pastries, coffee, and snacks, making it a great choice for any occasion. There are both indoor and outdoor seating options, with the indoor space thoughtfully divided into different zones for dining, coffee, or a mix of both.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/YLE4rYn9gJD3JTq68">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Ban Fa Prong Restaurant, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Sakon Nakhon Airport</name>
      <description><![CDATA[By Flight: The fastest way to get to Sakon Nakhon is to fly from Bangkok to  operated by AirAsia and it should take about one hour. You can browse more flights via Skyscanner.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/CfJKmrMXbQw3emCTA">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Sakon Nakhon Airport, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark>
    <Placemark>
      <name>Morchit Bus Terminal</name>
      <description><![CDATA[By Bus: You can also take a bus from Bangkok to Sakon Nakhon. The bus typically leaves from  and will drop you off at Sakon Nakhon Bus Terminal 2 in about 9.5 hours. The price is about 650 THB and you can find the schedule and book online here.<br><br><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/JLxvSFM72LAymGYv9">Open in Google Maps</a>]]></description>
      <address>Morchit Bus Terminal, Thailand</address>
    </Placemark></Document></kml>